, and a concurrent gout flare in his right great toe was managed with colchicine and his home allopurinol regimen.\n\nComprehensive Discharge Summary: Mr. ___ is a 67-year-old male discharged following a laparoscopic cholecystectomy for cholecystitis. His hospital course included the management of mild gallstone pancreatitis and a gout flare. He was discharged in stable condition on postoperative day 1 with a regular diet, instructions for activity restriction (no heavy lifting >10 lbs for 6 weeks), and a plan for follow-up in the general surgery clinic in 1-2 weeks. Medications at discharge include oxycodone and acetaminophen for pain management, stool softeners, and his chronic home medications.",
